# Controller Conventions

## Thin Controllers, Rich Models

Controllers orchestrate — they receive requests, delegate to models, and respond. Business logic belongs on the model. If a controller action has more than a handful of lines, logic is leaking.

```ruby
# Good — controller delegates to model verb
def create
  @card.close(by: Current.user)
  redirect_to @card
end

# Bad — business logic in controller
def create
  @card.update!(closed: true, closed_at: Time.current, closed_by: Current.user)
  @card.watchers.each { |w| NotifyJob.perform_later(w, @card) }
  redirect_to @card
end
```

## Everything Maps to CRUD

Custom actions become new resources. Instead of verbs on existing resources, create noun controllers with standard CRUD actions.

```ruby
# Good — noun resource with CRUD
resource :closure       # Cards::ClosuresController#create / #destroy
resource :archival      # Cards::ArchivalsController#create
resources :assignments  # Cards::AssignmentsController#create / #destroy

# Bad — verb actions on parent controller
post :close
post :archive
post :assign
```

## Controller Structure

Organise every controller in this order:

```ruby
class ArticlesController < ApplicationController
  # 1. Concerns
  include Sortable

  # 2. Security / rate limiting
  rate_limit to: 10, within: 3.minutes, only: :create

  # 3. Callbacks (before_action, after_action)
  before_action :set_article, only: %i[ show edit update destroy ]

  # 4. Public actions — index, show, new, create, edit, update, destroy
  def index
    @articles = policy_scope(Article).chronologically
    authorize Article
  end

  def show
    authorize @article
  end

  private
    # 5. Resource finders (memoised)
    def set_article
      @article = Article.find(params[:id])
    end

    # 6. Strong parameters
    def article_params
      params.expect(article: %i[ title body ])
    end
end
```

## Response Hierarchy

Prefer the simplest mechanism that satisfies the UX. Each step adds controller complexity — resist climbing until you must:

1. **Morphing** — `redirect_to` after mutation. Plain controller code, no format negotiation. Default.
2. **Turbo Frames** — scoped partial updates. Controller still renders normally.
3. **Turbo Streams** — surgical multi-target DOM updates. Last resort.

Maximise use of `redirect_to`. See the Turbo rules for implementation detail.

## Strong Parameters with `params.expect`

Prefer `params.expect` over `params.require(...).permit(...)` — it is the Rails 8+ convention, more concise, and raises on missing keys.

```ruby
def article_params
  params.expect(article: %i[ title body visibility ])
end
```

## Scoped Finders for Nested Resources

For nested resources, always scope record lookups through the parent association:

```ruby
# Good — scoped through parent
def set_comment
  @comment = @article.comments.find(params[:id])
end

# Bad — unscoped lookup for a nested resource
def set_comment
  @comment = Comment.find(params[:id])
end
```

Top-level resources use `Model.find(params[:id])` directly — scoping only applies when a resource is nested under a parent.

## Authentication (Rails 8+)

Rails 8 ships a built-in authentication generator (`bin/rails generate authentication`). Controllers require authentication by default and opt out explicitly:

```ruby
class ApplicationController < ActionController::Base
  include Authentication
end

class SessionsController < ApplicationController
  allow_unauthenticated_access
  rate_limit to: 10, within: 3.minutes, only: :create
end
```

## Authorization with Pundit

Use Pundit for authorization. Call `authorize` in every action — including `index`. Use `policy_scope` in `index` to filter records, then call `authorize` (usually `authorize Article` after scoping; see the policies rule). See the policies rule for full conventions.

```ruby
class ArticlesController < ApplicationController
  def index
    @articles = policy_scope(Article).chronologically
    authorize Article
  end

  def update
    @article = Article.find(params[:id])
    authorize @article

    if @article.update(article_params)
      redirect_to @article
    else
      render :edit, status: :unprocessable_content
    end
  end
end
```

Default: every action calls `authorize`. Use `after_action :verify_authorized` (and typically `after_action :verify_policy_scoped, only: :index`) in `ApplicationController`. For actions that intentionally need no authorization (public pages, health checks), use `skip_after_action` — see the policies skill § Skipping Verification.

```ruby
class ApplicationController < ActionController::Base
  include Pundit::Authorization

  after_action :verify_authorized
  after_action :verify_policy_scoped, only: :index

  rescue_from Pundit::NotAuthorizedError, with: :user_not_authorized

  private
    def user_not_authorized
      flash[:alert] = "You are not authorized to perform this action."
      redirect_back_or_to(root_path)
    end
end
```

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Instead |
|-------------|---------|
| Business logic in actions | Model method or domain verb |
| Custom verb actions (`close`, `archive`) | New noun resource with CRUD |
| `params.require(...).permit(...)` | `params.expect(...)` |
| Reaching for Turbo Streams first | Morphing → frames → streams (see Turbo rules) |
| Unscoped find for nested resources | Scope through parent association |
| `redirect_to` after failed save | `render :action, status: :unprocessable_content` |
| Multiple `before_action` setting the same chain | Base controller concern or inheritance |
| `rescue => e` in actions | `rescue_from` at the controller class level |
| Inline `current_user.admin?` permission checks | `authorize @record` delegates to policy |
| Pundit policy checks in `before_action` | `authorize` in the action body — keep `before_action` for authentication and finders, not permission rules |
| Forgetting authorization in an action | `after_action :verify_authorized` catches it |
| Forgetting `policy_scope` on index | `after_action :verify_policy_scoped, only: :index` catches it (when enabled) |
